data.title: "The Go-Between" by L.P. Hartley: A Bildungsroman Exploration of Class, Innocence, and Relationships
data.meta_description: Explore 'The Go-Between' by L.P. Hartley, a tale of class, innocence, and love's complexities in Edwardian England.
data.text:
The novel critiques the rigid social codes of Edwardian England and their stifling effect on individual desires and relationships

Leo's involvement in an illicit affair leads to a traumatic awakening and marks the end of his childhood innocence

The novel delves into the nature of memory and the passage of time, with Leo's role as a messenger of the gods highlighting his youthful innocence

The novel chronicles Leo's moral and psychological growth from an innocent boy to a disillusioned adult

Leo's childhood is characterized by wonder and a belief in the supernatural, but his involvement in adult affairs leads to a loss of innocence

Leo's traumatic experiences lead to emotional detachment and a lifetime marked by the effects of his past
